english:
  title: On Climbing Trees
  author: Kang Hi-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Two young woodcutters, A and B, worked together in the mountains. B possessed a nimble nature and moved through the forest with the swiftness of a monkey, gathering much fine kindling. A was timid and unskilled at climbing, so he could only collect dried grass to barely supplement their fuel for cooking.

    B boasted to A: "You don't know the way of woodcutting. Fine kindling doesn't grow on level ground. At first, I gathered all day and couldn't fill even one bundle—exhausted with little to show. So I studied the art of climbing trees. My feet ached at first, my heart trembled, and looking down I feared I'd fall. But gradually I grew steadier. After a month, climbing felt as easy as walking on flat earth. Searching this way, I reached places others cannot go. The higher I climbed, the more fine kindling I found. Thus I learned that those content with common places gain no extraordinary rewards."

    A smiled and replied: "You stand at the treetop, I stand at ground level. Our positions differ greatly, yet I cannot know—from my perspective—whether what is distant from me is truly high or low. Nor can you know—from your perspective—whether what is distant from you is not low. What we call high may not be high; what we call low may not be low. High and not-high, low and not-low—these are not for you and me to determine. Those who gain great profit plant seeds of great calamity. Those who rush to reap their rewards find ruin comes swiftly. Abandon this path. I will not follow your way."

    B had no reply.

    A month later, B climbed a hundred-foot pine on a cliff to gather kindling. His hand slipped. He fell to earth and lost consciousness. His father carried him home and poured urine into his mouth. After a long time he revived. Months passed before he could swallow broth. Both his legs were broken. Both his eyes were lost. He became like a corpse walking.

    His father brought him to A, asking to hear A's teaching on high and low. A spoke thus:

    "High and low have no fixed place. They bear no permanent names. Where there is below, there must be above. Without lowness, how could height exist? Through the low, we become high. Climbing upward begins from below. Thus the high is an accumulation of the low; descent is the pathway to ascent.

    Those who dwell constantly in heights find their heights easily become low. Those who delight in climbing find their ascent can become descent. When the high lose their height and seek peace in the low, they cannot find it. When those above lose their position and wish to rest below, they cannot rest.

    By this logic: is not the low superior to the high? Is not descent superior to ascent?

    When B gathered kindling, he loved only ascent and despised descent. He craved height and hated lowness. How could he not come to ruin?

    Woodcutters naturally desire fine kindling. Fine kindling grows abundantly in the treetops because danger guards it there. B coveted the gain and forgot the peril. He did not know that each hand-span higher brings each hand-span more danger; that the farther from earth, the lower the body becomes. To boast of this to others—is it not foolish?

    B and I have gathered wood together long. In one day, I harvest barely half what B once gathered. Yet I do not lament. I possess a way to endure. Why? B reaped his harvest in the most treacherous places and became broken in his youth. Though he wished to extend his labor into later years, it is now impossible. I, though mediocre, have not ceased my work. I will gather wood until I die of old age. Then who truly gathered much and who gathered little? Who truly climbed high and who remained low?"

    B's father returned and told his son these words. Together they wept in anguish. Only then did B understand the wisdom in A's first teaching.

    Old men in Geumyang who hear this tale write it as a warning to their children and grandchildren.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Geumyang (金陽) is a region name; it refers to an area of moral influence where the teaching spreads.
  - key: ''
    value: The dialogue plays on Buddhist and Daoist philosophical concepts of relativity and the illusion of fixed positions—high and low are not absolute states but perspectives shaped by attachment and desire.
